tions of classical mythology—ranges from the practical, psychologically astute, and profound to the ironic, deliberately offensive, and bizarre. Some advice is conventional—such as staying busy, not spending time alone, and avoiding places associated with an ex. Some is off-color, such as having sex until you’re sick of it. And some is simply and delightfully weird—such as becoming a lawyer and not eating arugula.Whether his advice is good or bad, entertaining or outrageous, How to Get Over a Breakup reveals an Ovid who sounds startlingly modern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLove poetry. 0aSeparation (Psychology)vPoetry. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAchilles.  aAddiction.  aAgamemnon.  aApollo.  aArms.  aArrows.  aArts.  aBlood.  aBodies.  aBreak.  aBull.  aCupid.  aDaughter.  aDeath.  aDisease.  aDivorce.  aDoor.  aEm.  aEx.  aFall.  aFields.  aFlames.  aFun.  aGirlfriend.  aGrapes.  aGuy.  aHang.  aHard.  aHate.  aHeart.  aHelen.  aHit.  aHorse.  aHurt.  aIllness.  aLove.  aLover.  aNote.  aOnset.  aOught.  aOvid.  aPasiphae.  aPhyllis.  aPoem.  aRelief.  aRivers.  aSad.  aSea.  aSeeds.  aSex.  aSick.  aSleep.  aSpear.  aStomach.  aStop.  aStrength.  aStyle.  aTears.  aTorch.  aTreatment.  aTree.  aTricks.  aTriumph.  aUlysses.  aVenus.  aWar.  aWater.  aWife.  aWrong.  a~author.1 aFontaine, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122031440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691220314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97806912